2005230507152290146,"Selective Outcomes Arbitrage on PolymarketThis strategy is used by less than 5% of traders but it brings 100% profit almost every time in the long runIt works on multi outcome marketsIn my case it's Super Bowl Champion 2026I buy YES from the top down until total cost gets close to around 0.90¢Rams - 16.3¢ → 0.163Seattle - 12.5¢ → 0.288Buffalo - 11.0¢ → 0.398Denver - 10.2¢ → 0.500Philadelphia - 9.0¢ → 0.590New England - 7.5¢ → 0.665San Francisco - 7.3¢ → 0.738Houston - 5.8¢ → 0.796Jacksonville - 5.8¢ → 0.854Chicago - 5.1¢ → 0.905I stop at Green Bay - the total portfolio is around 0.90 already and I want to leave about 10¢ upside on any hitIf any of these 10 teams take the Super Bowl, payout = 1$, net profit is around 9.9¢ or roughly 10% ROI///Across other multi outcome sports markets:CFB - in college football the title almost always goes to programs from the same elite pool that open the season near the top of the odds, so true underdog runs are rare and the selective top coverage gives less value for the riskNBA - even harder here, almost every champion came from a top 3 regular season seed, and low seeds only won the title a couple times in history, so the bulk YES buy down the table doesn’t really pay off long termSoccer (World Cup) - at World Cups and big tournaments the winner is almost always from the top 8 pre tourn odds, and teams from the bottom never reach the title, so multi outcome coverage there has poor EV///Why NFL - the league shows a rare combo. Champs mostly come from upper part of the preseason odds, but longshots pop off pretty often - like Raiders in 1981, 49ers in 1995, Rams in 1999 or Patriots in 200211 of the last 16 champs were underdogs in the final itself, which makes partial top coverage up to around 0.9$ especially attractive on risk reward basis///What do you think about this strategy, Polyfrens?Super Bowl Champion 2026 market: https://t.co/V82omWHS3H",2025-12-28,immortalhowwl,30230.0,,Super Bowl LX,
