2020999135621517422,"23% of Super Bowl ads mentioned AI.That number landed differently depending on who watched.Creative professionals saw repetition. Marketing teams saw validation. Fans posting on social media saw another trend getting overplayed. ""AI Bowl"" became the nickname before halftime.The fatigue was real.But the volume wasn't random.These weren't product launches. Most ads didn't explain features or show use cases. They showed AI existing in daily routines. Ordering groceries. Answering questions. Managing schedules. The work wasn't in the selling. It was in the placement.Repeated exposure changes how something registers. First time feels new. Fifth time feels normal. Tenth time feels expected. By the time 23% of the night's ads reference the same technology, the question shifts from ""do I need this"" to ""which version do I need.""That's not speculation. That's how category normalization works in advertising. Make the concept familiar before the purchase decision arrives.Super Bowl ads cost millions per slot. Companies don't spend that to test creative concepts. They spend it to claim mental real estate when attention is concentrated. 23% percent of that real estate went to conditioning acceptance, not driving immediate action.The complaints about oversaturation are valid. But they confirm the strategy worked. We're debating execution quality instead of examining why this much budget went toward making AI feel unavoidable.Fatigue means the message landed.Where have you noticed AI showing up without asking for it?",2026-02-09,EricJohnAndal,24.0,,Super Bowl LX,
